      "solution": "I=input\nN=int(I())+2\nL,R=\"\\\\\",\"/\"\ns=L+I()+R\nr=\"\"\ni,j,k=0,s.find(L,1),s.find(R)\nwhile(i>=N)+(j==k<0)<1:l=(j,k)[j<0 or k<j];m=l-i+1;n=m//2;r+=((R*(n-1)+\"|\"*(m%2)+L*n,s[i+1:l+1])[s[i]>R],s[i]*(m-1))[s[l]==s[i]];i=l;exec(f\"{'jk'[k==l]}=s.find({'LR'[k==l]},{l+1})\")\nprint(r[:-1])",
      "statement": "A bookshelf contains [[N]] books arranged in a row. Each book starts in one of three positions: upright ({{|}}), leaning left ({{\\}}), or leaning right ({{/}}).\n\n● A book that's leaning left will push on the book <<directly to its left>>, causing that book to <<lean left>> if it was previously upright. For example, {{|\\}} → {{\\\\}}.\n● A book that's leaning right will push on the book <<directly to its right>>, causing that book to <<lean right>> if it was previously upright. For example, {{/|}} → {{//}}.\n● Books pushing on each other or getting pushed on with <<opposing forces>> will <<stop moving>> (no change in position). For example, {{/\\}} → {{/\\}} and {{/|\\}} → {{/|\\}}.\n\nThe books are allowed to lean on one another from their starting positions until all of the books stop moving. Given the starting positions of the books, what will the bookshelf look like at the end?",
